Objective: we have to identify the factors affecting attrition.

  • Hypothesis 1: ### Age of the employee: can have some impact on the attrition. Studies and surveys have shown that employees are more likely to switch jobs during the early stages of their career. So it may be possible that higher the age, less likely the attrition.

code:

hist(data$Age, 
     main = "Histogram of employees age", # title of the histogram
     xlab="Employees age",
     ylab = "No. of employees",
     col = "gold", 
     border = "green", 
     las = 1, 
     labels = T

     # and size of intervals in data (bins) and focus on those distributions
     
)

## This is a numerical column. we can see that employees age distribution is a bit right skewed, with most being in the age 30-35

creating a column ‘Age bin’ in the range (20,60 with 20 as bin size) to see

the relation bewtween attrition vs Age.

data8 <- data
data8$Agebin <-cut(data$Age,labels=seq(20,40,20), 
                            breaks = seq(20,60,20))

# % attrition  vs non-attrition - Agebin
# table indicates the conditional probablity ie P(attrition status| the Age bin). 
round(prop.table(table(data8$Attrition,data8$Agebin), margin=2),2)*100
##    
##     20 40
##   0 83 89
##   1 17 11
barplot(table(data8$Attrition, data8$Agebin), 
        legend.text = T, 
        xlab= 'Age-bin', 
        ylab='frequency',
        main= 'barplot of Attrition vs Agebin')

bar plot of the YearsAtCompany vs Attrition

We can see higher the age, lower the attrition, supporting the hypothesis

  • Hypothesis 2:

Business travel: represents how frequently an employee has to travel for the job. Though there may be a factor of tiredness due to frequent travel, employee would mostly know about the travel frequency before joining the job, so this may have negligible impact on the attrition of the employee

barplot(table(data$BusinessTravel ), # table used to get counts of each group 
        main = "Bar plot to show business travel frequency and count of employees in each.", # Title we want 
                # to give to the bar plot  
        xlab = "Business Travel frequency", # Used to give label to the x axis
        ylab = "Number of employees", # Used to give label to the y axis
        col = "pink", # used to give colour to the bars for visual appeal 
        border = 'blue', # used to denote border and outliers colour to distinguish and 
        # visual appeal
        horiz = F, # boolean to denote whether we want the bars to be horizontal
        las = 1, # see both y-axis and x axis values horizontally, used when we want to see the 
        # axes values clearly and avoid overlap with other values
        )

## This is a categorical column. We can see that majority employees travel rarely

data$BusinessTravel <- as.factor(data$BusinessTravel)

Bivariate: Attrition grouped by business travel

barplot(table(data$Attrition, data$BusinessTravel),
        col = c("green", "red"), # used to indicate the colours we want
              # for each of the bars in the group
        beside = T,   # used to indicate when we want the bars to be besides each other in the groups
        main = "Bar plot to show number of employess by Businees travel and attrition", 
        xlab = "Business travel frequency", 
        ylab = "Number of employees", 
        las = 1,
        space = c(1,2), # specify number of spaces within and between groups of bars, used when 
                #we want to add spaces between bars for clarity
        )

# use legend function to add more info to the bar plot (more useful than legend.text in barplot)
## new arguments explored: position, values, fill, title
legend("topright", # specify position where we want to add legend in the plot 
       c("0", "1"), # specify values for which we want to add legend 
       fill = c("green","red"), # specify colour we want to fill for 
              # each corresponding legend value
       title = "Attrition" # specify the tile of the legend
       )

We can see that highest count of attrition is in case of rare travel and least in non- travel

But we may need to get proportion of attriton in each group as the number of employees in each group is different

round(prop.table(table(data$Attrition, data$BusinessTravel), 2), 2) * 100
##    
##     Non-Travel Travel_Frequently Travel_Rarely

##   1          8                25            15

        col = c("green", "red"), # used to indicate the colours we want
              # for each of the bars in the group
        beside = T,   # used to indicate when we want the bars to be besides each other in the groups
        main = "Bar plot to show proportion of attrition in each BusinessTravel group",
